    <h1>C_Discrete Mathematics</h1>
    <div class=3D"Section1">
        <h2 id=3D"C_DiscreteMathematics-Theory"><code>Theory</code></h2>
<ol start=3D"1">
<li>
<p>Discrete Mathematics, Theory of Computation and Basic Graph Theory Set t=
heory;</p></li>
<li>
<p>Relations;</p></li>
<li>
<p>Functions;</p></li>
<li>
<p>Graph theory;</p></li>
<li>
<p>Propositional calculus and predicate calculus;</p></li>
<li>
<p>Mathematical reasoning: induction, contradiction and recursion;</p></li>
<li>
<p>Counting; Principles of inclusion and exclusion;</p></li>
<li>
<p>Recurrence relations;</p></li>
<li>
<p>Algebraic structures: rings and groups.</p></li>
</ol>
<p></p>
<ol start=3D"1">
<li>
<p>Discrete Mathematics, Theory of Computation and Basic Graph Theory Set t=
heory;</p></li>
</ol>
<p>Let=E2=80=99s break down and explain the first topic from <strong>Discre=
te Mathematics, Theory of Computation, and Basic Graph Theory</strong> =E2=
=80=94 starting with <strong>Set Theory</strong> =F0=9F=91=87</p>
<hr>
<h2 id=3D"C_DiscreteMathematics-=F0=9F=A7=A91.SetTheory=E2=80=93Overview">=
=F0=9F=A7=A9 <strong>1. Set Theory =E2=80=93 Overview</strong></h2>
<p><strong>Set Theory</strong> is the foundation of discrete mathematics.<b=
r>
A <strong>set</strong> is a <strong>collection of distinct, well-defined ob=
jects</strong> (called <em>elements</em> or <em>members</em>).</p>
<p>Example:<br>
A =3D {1, 2, 3, 4}<br>
Here, the numbers 1, 2, 3, and 4 are <strong>elements</strong> of the set <=
strong>A</strong>.</p>
<hr>
<h2 id=3D"C_DiscreteMathematics-=E2=9C=B3=EF=B8=8F2.RepresentationofSets">=
=E2=9C=B3=EF=B8=8F <strong>2. Representation of Sets</strong></h2>
<ol start=3D"1">
<li>
<p><strong>Roster form:</strong> Listing all elements<br>
=E2=86=92 A =3D {2, 4, 6, 8}</p></li>
<li>
<p><strong>Set-builder form:</strong> Describes elements using a property<b=
r>
=E2=86=92 A =3D {x | x is an even number less than 10}</p></li>
</ol>
<hr>
<h2 id=3D"C_DiscreteMathematics-=E2=9A=99=EF=B8=8F3.TypesofSets">=E2=9A=99=
=EF=B8=8F <strong>3. Types of Sets</strong></h2>
<div class=3D"table-wrap">
<table data-layout=3D"default" data-local-id=3D"b9fa86e3-b7f3-43f2-86e2-e5d=
f31e4ba17" class=3D"confluenceTable">
<tbody>
<tr>
<th class=3D"confluenceTh">
<p>Type</p></th>
<th class=3D"confluenceTh">
<p>Example</p></th>
<th class=3D"confluenceTh">
<p>Description</p></th>
</tr>
<tr>
<td class=3D"confluenceTd">
<p><strong>Finite set</strong></p></td>
<td class=3D"confluenceTd">
<p>{1, 2, 3}</p></td>
<td class=3D"confluenceTd">
<p>Limited number of elements</p></td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td class=3D"confluenceTd">
<p><strong>Infinite set</strong></p></td>
<td class=3D"confluenceTd">
<p>{1, 2, 3, =E2=80=A6}</p></td>
<td class=3D"confluenceTd">
<p>Unlimited elements</p></td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td class=3D"confluenceTd">
<p><strong>Null (empty) set</strong></p></td>
<td class=3D"confluenceTd">
<p>{ } or =C3=98</p></td>
<td class=3D"confluenceTd">
<p>No elements</p></td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td class=3D"confluenceTd">
<p><strong>Singleton set</strong></p></td>
<td class=3D"confluenceTd">
<p>{a}</p></td>
<td class=3D"confluenceTd">
<p>Only one element</p></td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td class=3D"confluenceTd">
<p><strong>Equal sets</strong></p></td>
<td class=3D"confluenceTd">
<p>{1, 2, 3} =3D {3, 2, 1}</p></td>
<td class=3D"confluenceTd">
<p>Same elements</p></td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td class=3D"confluenceTd">
<p><strong>Subset</strong></p></td>
<td class=3D"confluenceTd">
<p>A =E2=8A=86 B</p></td>
<td class=3D"confluenceTd">
<p>All elements of A are in B</p></td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td class=3D"confluenceTd">
<p><strong>Proper subset</strong></p></td>
<td class=3D"confluenceTd">
<p>A =E2=8A=82 B</p></td>
<td class=3D"confluenceTd">
<p>A =E2=8A=86 B but A =E2=89=A0 B</p></td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td class=3D"confluenceTd">
<p><strong>Universal set (U)</strong></p></td>
<td class=3D"confluenceTd">
<p>All possible elements under discussion</p></td>
<td class=3D"confluenceTd">
<p></p></td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td class=3D"confluenceTd">
<p><strong>Complement (A=E2=80=B2)</strong></p></td>
<td class=3D"confluenceTd">
<p>Elements not in A but in U</p></td>
<td class=3D"confluenceTd">
<p></p></td>
</tr>
</tbody>
</table>
</div>
<hr>
<h2 id=3D"C_DiscreteMathematics-=F0=9F=94=814.SetOperations">=F0=9F=94=81 <=
strong>4. Set Operations</strong></h2>
<div class=3D"table-wrap">
<table data-layout=3D"default" data-local-id=3D"c709e02c-f253-4d41-a254-0a5=
872c46e0c" class=3D"confluenceTable">
<tbody>
<tr>
<th class=3D"confluenceTh">
<p>Operation</p></th>
<th class=3D"confluenceTh">
<p>Symbol</p></th>
<th class=3D"confluenceTh">
<p>Description</p></th>
<th class=3D"confluenceTh">
<p>Example</p></th>
</tr>
<tr>
<td class=3D"confluenceTd">
<p><strong>Union</strong></p></td>
<td class=3D"confluenceTd">
<p>A =E2=88=AA B</p></td>
<td class=3D"confluenceTd">
<p>All elements in A or B or both</p></td>
<td class=3D"confluenceTd">
<p>{1,2} =E2=88=AA {2,3} =3D {1,2,3}</p></td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td class=3D"confluenceTd">
<p><strong>Intersection</strong></p></td>
<td class=3D"confluenceTd">
<p>A =E2=88=A9 B</p></td>
<td class=3D"confluenceTd">
<p>Elements common to A and B</p></td>
<td class=3D"confluenceTd">
<p>{1,2} =E2=88=A9 {2,3} =3D {2}</p></td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td class=3D"confluenceTd">
<p><strong>Difference</strong></p></td>
<td class=3D"confluenceTd">
<p>A =E2=80=93 B</p></td>
<td class=3D"confluenceTd">
<p>Elements in A but not in B</p></td>
<td class=3D"confluenceTd">
<p>{1,2,3} =E2=80=93 {2,3} =3D {1}</p></td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td class=3D"confluenceTd">
<p><strong>Complement</strong></p></td>
<td class=3D"confluenceTd">
<p>A=E2=80=B2</p></td>
<td class=3D"confluenceTd">
<p>Elements not in A</p></td>
<td class=3D"confluenceTd">
<p>If U =3D {1,2,3,4}, A=3D{1,2} =E2=86=92 A=E2=80=B2=3D{3,4}</p></td>
</tr>
</tbody>
</table>
</div>
<hr>
<h2 id=3D"C_DiscreteMathematics-=F0=9F=A7=AE5.LawsofSetAlgebra">=F0=9F=A7=
=AE <strong>5. Laws of Set Algebra</strong></h2>
<div class=3D"table-wrap">
<table data-layout=3D"default" data-local-id=3D"ddbdc756-911e-42be-9ef7-cef=
2eb330616" class=3D"confluenceTable">
<tbody>
<tr>
<th class=3D"confluenceTh">
<p>Law</p></th>
<th class=3D"confluenceTh">
<p>Expression</p></th>
</tr>
<tr>
<td class=3D"confluenceTd">
<p><strong>Commutative Law</strong></p></td>
<td class=3D"confluenceTd">
<p>A =E2=88=AA B =3D B =E2=88=AA A, =E2=80=83A =E2=88=A9 B =3D B =E2=88=A9 =
A</p></td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td class=3D"confluenceTd">
<p><strong>Associative Law</strong></p></td>
<td class=3D"confluenceTd">
<p>(A =E2=88=AA B) =E2=88=AA C =3D A =E2=88=AA (B =E2=88=AA C)</p></td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td class=3D"confluenceTd">
<p><strong>Distributive Law</strong></p></td>
<td class=3D"confluenceTd">
<p>A =E2=88=A9 (B =E2=88=AA C) =3D (A =E2=88=A9 B) =E2=88=AA (A =E2=88=A9 C=
)</p></td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td class=3D"confluenceTd">
<p><strong>Identity Law</strong></p></td>
<td class=3D"confluenceTd">
<p>A =E2=88=AA =E2=88=85 =3D A,=E2=80=83A =E2=88=A9 U =3D A</p></td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td class=3D"confluenceTd">
<p><strong>Complement Law</strong></p></td>
<td class=3D"confluenceTd">
<p>A =E2=88=AA A=E2=80=B2 =3D U,=E2=80=83A =E2=88=A9 A=E2=80=B2 =3D =E2=88=
=85</p></td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td class=3D"confluenceTd">
<p><strong>Idempotent Law</strong></p></td>
<td class=3D"confluenceTd">
<p>A =E2=88=AA A =3D A,=E2=80=83A =E2=88=A9 A =3D A</p></td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td class=3D"confluenceTd">
<p><strong>De Morgan=E2=80=99s Laws</strong></p></td>
<td class=3D"confluenceTd">
<p>(A =E2=88=AA B)=E2=80=B2 =3D A=E2=80=B2 =E2=88=A9 B=E2=80=B2,=E2=80=83(A=
 =E2=88=A9 B)=E2=80=B2 =3D A=E2=80=B2 =E2=88=AA B=E2=80=B2</p></td>
</tr>
</tbody>
</table>
</div>
<hr>
<h2 id=3D"C_DiscreteMathematics-=F0=9F=94=B96.VennDiagrams">=F0=9F=94=B9 <s=
trong>6. Venn Diagrams</strong></h2>
<ul>
<li>
<p>A <strong>Venn Diagram</strong> visually represents the relationships be=
tween sets using circles.</p></li>
<li>
<p>It helps understand <strong>union, intersection, difference,</strong> an=
d <strong>complement</strong> operations.</p></li>
</ul>
<hr>
<h2 id=3D"C_DiscreteMathematics-=F0=9F=93=987.CartesianProductofSets">=F0=
=9F=93=98 <strong>7. Cartesian Product of Sets</strong></h2>
<p>If <strong>A</strong> and <strong>B</strong> are two sets, then<br>
[<br>
A =C3=97 B =3D { (a, b) | a =E2=88=88 A, b =E2=88=88 B }<br>
]<br>
Example:<br>
A =3D {1, 2}, B =3D {x, y}<br>
=E2=86=92 A =C3=97 B =3D {(1, x), (1, y), (2, x), (2, y)}</p>
<hr>
<h2 id=3D"C_DiscreteMathematics-=E2=9C=858.ApplicationsofSetTheory">=E2=9C=
=85 <strong>8. Applications of Set Theory</strong></h2>
<ul>
<li>
<p>Database management (relations, queries)</p></li>
<li>
<p>Logic circuits (AND =3D =E2=88=A9, OR =3D =E2=88=AA, NOT =3D complement)=
</p></li>
<li>
<p>Probability and statistics</p></li>
<li>
<p>Computer programming (collections, arrays)</p></li>
<li>
<p>Artificial intelligence and automata theory</p></li>
</ul>
<hr>
<h3 id=3D"C_DiscreteMathematics-Inshort:"><strong>In short:</strong></h3>
<ul>
<li>
<p><strong>Set theory</strong> provides the foundation for all mathematical=
 logic and computation.</p></li>
<li>
<p>Operations like <strong>union</strong>, <strong>intersection</strong>, a=
nd <strong>complement</strong> are similar to logical <strong>OR</strong>, =
<strong>AND</strong>, and <strong>NOT</strong>.</p></li>
<li>
<p>Widely used in algorithms, databases, and theoretical computer science.<=
/p></li>
</ul>
<ol start=3D"2">
<li>
<p>Relations; Functions;</p></li>
</ol>
<p>Let=E2=80=99s explain <strong>Relations</strong> and <strong>Functions</=
strong>, which are fundamental topics in <strong>Discrete Mathematics</stro=
ng>.</p>
<hr>
<h2 id=3D"C_DiscreteMathematics-=F0=9F=A7=A91.Relations">=F0=9F=A7=A9 <stro=
ng>1. Relations</strong></h2>
<h3 id=3D"C_DiscreteMathematics-=F0=9F=94=B9Definition">=F0=9F=94=B9 Defini=
tion</h3>
<p>A <strong>relation</strong> from set <strong>A</strong> to set <strong>B=
</strong> is a <strong>subset of the Cartesian product</strong> (A \times B=
).</p>
<ul>
<li>
<p>It shows how elements of <strong>A</strong> are related to elements of <=
strong>B</strong>.</p></li>
</ul>
<p>[<br>
R \subseteq A \times B<br>
]</p>
<p><strong>Example:</strong><br>
A =3D {1, 2, 3}, B =3D {x, y}<br>
R =3D {(1, x), (2, y)} =E2=86=92 a relation from A to B</p>
<hr>
<h3 id=3D"C_DiscreteMathematics-=F0=9F=94=B9TypesofRelations">=F0=9F=94=B9 =
Types of Relations</h3>
<ol start=3D"1">
<li>
<p><strong>Reflexive:</strong> Every element relates to itself</p>
<ul>
<li>
<p>(a, a) =E2=88=88 R for all a =E2=88=88 A</p></li>
</ul></li>
<li>
<p><strong>Symmetric:</strong> If (a, b) =E2=88=88 R =E2=86=92 (b, a) =E2=
=88=88 R</p></li>
<li>
<p><strong>Transitive:</strong> If (a, b) =E2=88=88 R and (b, c) =E2=88=88 =
R =E2=86=92 (a, c) =E2=88=88 R</p></li>
<li>
<p><strong>Antisymmetric:</strong> If (a, b) =E2=88=88 R and (b, a) =E2=88=
=88 R =E2=86=92 a =3D b</p></li>
<li>
<p><strong>Equivalence Relation:</strong> Reflexive, symmetric, and transit=
ive</p></li>
</ol>
<hr>
<h3 id=3D"C_DiscreteMathematics-=F0=9F=94=B9RepresentationofRelations">=F0=
=9F=94=B9 Representation of Relations</h3>
<ul>
<li>
<p><strong>Set of ordered pairs:</strong> R =3D {(1, x), (2, y)}</p></li>
<li>
<p><strong>Matrix representation:</strong> R is represented as a 0-1 matrix=
</p></li>
<li>
<p><strong>Graphical representation:</strong> Elements are vertices; relati=
ons are edges</p></li>
</ul>
<hr>
<h2 id=3D"C_DiscreteMathematics-=E2=9A=A12.Functions">=E2=9A=A1 <strong>2. =
Functions</strong></h2>
<h3 id=3D"C_DiscreteMathematics-=F0=9F=94=B9Definition.1">=F0=9F=94=B9 Defi=
nition</h3>
<p>A <strong>function (or mapping)</strong> f from set <strong>A</strong> t=
o set <strong>B</strong> is a relation where <strong>every element of A map=
s to exactly one element of B</strong>.<br>
[<br>
f: A =E2=86=92 B<br>
]</p>
<ul>
<li>
<p><strong>Domain:</strong> Set A</p></li>
<li>
<p><strong>Codomain:</strong> Set B</p></li>
<li>
<p><strong>Range:</strong> Actual set of elements in B mapped from A</p></l=
i>
</ul>
<p><strong>Example:</strong><br>
A =3D {1, 2, 3}, B =3D {x, y, z}<br>
f =3D { (1, x), (2, y), (3, z) } =E2=86=92 function from A to B</p>
<hr>
<h3 id=3D"C_DiscreteMathematics-=F0=9F=94=B9TypesofFunctions">=F0=9F=94=B9 =
Types of Functions</h3>
<div class=3D"table-wrap">
<table data-layout=3D"default" data-local-id=3D"0628e796-9c81-4a07-a2e1-e65=
eac49c77d" class=3D"confluenceTable">
<tbody>
<tr>
<th class=3D"confluenceTh">
<p>Type</p></th>
<th class=3D"confluenceTh">
<p>Description</p></th>
<th class=3D"confluenceTh">
<p>Example</p></th>
</tr>
<tr>
<td class=3D"confluenceTd">
<p><strong>One-to-One (Injective)</strong></p></td>
<td class=3D"confluenceTd">
<p>No two elements of A map to the same element of B</p></td>
<td class=3D"confluenceTd">
<p>f(1)=3Dx, f(2)=3Dy</p></td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td class=3D"confluenceTd">
<p><strong>Onto (Surjective)</strong></p></td>
<td class=3D"confluenceTd">
<p>Every element of B is mapped by some element of A</p></td>
<td class=3D"confluenceTd">
<p>f: A=3D{1,2,3}, B=3D{x,y} (needs at least two A elements mapping to one =
B)</p></td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td class=3D"confluenceTd">
<p><strong>Bijective</strong></p></td>
<td class=3D"confluenceTd">
<p>Both one-to-one and onto</p></td>
<td class=3D"confluenceTd">
<p>Perfect pairing: each element maps uniquely and all B covered</p></td>
</tr>
</tbody>
</table>
</div>
<hr>
<h3 id=3D"C_DiscreteMathematics-=F0=9F=94=B9FunctionOperations">=F0=9F=94=
=B9 Function Operations</h3>
<ol start=3D"1">
<li>
<p><strong>Composition:</strong> (f =E2=88=98 g)(x) =3D f(g(x))</p></li>
<li>
<p><strong>Inverse function:</strong> f=E2=81=BB=C2=B9(y) =3D x if f(x) =3D=
 y</p></li>
<li>
<p><strong>Identity function:</strong> I(x) =3D x</p></li>
</ol>
<hr>
<h3 id=3D"C_DiscreteMathematics-=F0=9F=94=B9RepresentationofFunctions">=F0=
=9F=94=B9 Representation of Functions</h3>
<ul>
<li>
<p><strong>Set of ordered pairs:</strong> f =3D {(1, x), (2, y)}</p></li>
<li>
<p><strong>Mapping diagram:</strong> Arrows from elements of A to B</p></li=
>
<li>
<p><strong>Graphical:</strong> Plotting y =3D f(x)</p></li>
</ul>
<hr>
<h2 id=3D"C_DiscreteMathematics-=E2=9C=85KeyPoints">=E2=9C=85 <strong>Key P=
oints</strong></h2>
<ul>
<li>
<p><strong>Relation:</strong> Any association between elements of two sets.=
</p></li>
<li>
<p><strong>Function:</strong> Special relation where <strong>each input has=
 exactly one output</strong>.</p></li>
<li>
<p><strong>Function types</strong>: Injective, Surjective, Bijective.</p></=
li>
<li>
<p><strong>Applications:</strong> Databases, algorithms, discrete math prob=
lems, computer programming.</p></li>
</ul>
<hr>
<p>If you want, I can next explain <strong>Propositional Logic and Predicat=
e Logic</strong>, which is usually the continuation after Sets, Relations, =
and Functions.</p>
<ol start=3D"3">
<li>
<p>Graph theory;</p></li>
</ol>
<p>Let=E2=80=99s explain <strong>Graph Theory</strong>, which is a key part=
 of <strong>Discrete Mathematics</strong>.</p>
<hr>
<h2 id=3D"C_DiscreteMathematics-=F0=9F=A7=A91.Graph=E2=80=93BasicDefinition=
">=F0=9F=A7=A9 <strong>1. Graph =E2=80=93 Basic Definition</strong></h2>
<p>A <strong>graph</strong> (G) is a pair of sets:</p>
<p>[<br>
G =3D (V, E)<br>
]</p>
<ul>
<li>
<p><strong>V</strong> =3D set of vertices (nodes)</p></li>
<li>
<p><strong>E</strong> =3D set of edges (connections between vertices)</p></=
li>
</ul>
<p>An <strong>edge</strong> connects two vertices, represented as ( (u, v) =
) or ( u \sim v ).</p>
<hr>
<h2 id=3D"C_DiscreteMathematics-=F0=9F=94=B92.TypesofGraphs">=F0=9F=94=B9 <=
strong>2. Types of Graphs</strong></h2>
<div class=3D"table-wrap">
<table data-layout=3D"default" data-local-id=3D"b1297f00-46b0-451b-84ef-d19=
82556076b" class=3D"confluenceTable">
<tbody>
<tr>
<th class=3D"confluenceTh">
<p>Type</p></th>
<th class=3D"confluenceTh">
<p>Description</p></th>
<th class=3D"confluenceTh">
<p>Example</p></th>
</tr>
<tr>
<td class=3D"confluenceTd">
<p><strong>Undirected Graph</strong></p></td>
<td class=3D"confluenceTd">
<p>Edges have no direction</p></td>
<td class=3D"confluenceTd">
<p>Friendship network</p></td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td class=3D"confluenceTd">
<p><strong>Directed Graph (Digraph)</strong></p></td>
<td class=3D"confluenceTd">
<p>Edges have a direction</p></td>
<td class=3D"confluenceTd">
<p>Twitter follow network</p></td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td class=3D"confluenceTd">
<p><strong>Weighted Graph</strong></p></td>
<td class=3D"confluenceTd">
<p>Edges carry weights</p></td>
<td class=3D"confluenceTd">
<p>Road map with distances</p></td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td class=3D"confluenceTd">
<p><strong>Unweighted Graph</strong></p></td>
<td class=3D"confluenceTd">
<p>Edges have no weight</p></td>
<td class=3D"confluenceTd">
<p>Simple connections</p></td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td class=3D"confluenceTd">
<p><strong>Simple Graph</strong></p></td>
<td class=3D"confluenceTd">
<p>No loops or multiple edges</p></td>
<td class=3D"confluenceTd">
<p>Standard graph</p></td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td class=3D"confluenceTd">
<p><strong>Multigraph</strong></p></td>
<td class=3D"confluenceTd">
<p>Multiple edges allowed between vertices</p></td>
<td class=3D"confluenceTd">
<p>Transportation routes</p></td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td class=3D"confluenceTd">
<p><strong>Complete Graph (Kn)</strong></p></td>
<td class=3D"confluenceTd">
<p>Every vertex connected to every other</p></td>
<td class=3D"confluenceTd">
<p>Small network</p></td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td class=3D"confluenceTd">
<p><strong>Bipartite Graph</strong></p></td>
<td class=3D"confluenceTd">
<p>Vertex set divided into two, edges only between sets</p></td>
<td class=3D"confluenceTd">
<p>Job assignment problem</p></td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td class=3D"confluenceTd">
<p><strong>Cyclic Graph</strong></p></td>
<td class=3D"confluenceTd">
<p>Contains at least one cycle</p></td>
<td class=3D"confluenceTd">
<p>Polygon-like graph</p></td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td class=3D"confluenceTd">
<p><strong>Acyclic Graph</strong></p></td>
