<ol start=3D"5">
<li>
<p>Mathematical reasoning: induction, contradiction and recursion;</p></li>
</ol>
<p>Let=E2=80=99s explain <strong>Mathematical Reasoning</strong>, focusing =
on <strong>Induction, Contradiction, and Recursion</strong>, which are fund=
amental for discrete mathematics and algorithm design.</p>
<hr>
<h2 id=3D"C_DiscreteMathematics-=F0=9F=A7=A91.MathematicalReasoning=E2=80=
=93Overview">=F0=9F=A7=A9 <strong>1. Mathematical Reasoning =E2=80=93 Overv=
iew</strong></h2>
<p>Mathematical reasoning is the <strong>logical process of deducing conclu=
sions from given statements or premises</strong>.<br>
It is used to <strong>prove theorems, validate algorithms, and reason about=
 discrete structures</strong>.</p>
<hr>
<h2 id=3D"C_DiscreteMathematics-=F0=9F=94=B92.MathematicalInduction">=F0=9F=
=94=B9 <strong>2. Mathematical Induction</strong></h2>
<h3 id=3D"C_DiscreteMathematics-Definition">Definition</h3>
<p><strong>Mathematical induction</strong> is a technique to prove statemen=
ts <strong>about natural numbers</strong>.<br>
It consists of two steps:</p>
<ol start=3D"1">
<li>
<p><strong>Base Case:</strong> Verify the statement is true for the first v=
alue (usually n =3D 0 or 1).</p></li>
<li>
<p><strong>Induction Step:</strong> Assume the statement is true for n =3D =
k (<strong>induction hypothesis</strong>) and prove it is true for n =3D k =
+ 1.</p></li>
</ol>
<p>If both steps are valid, the statement holds for all n =E2=89=A5 base va=
lue.</p>
<h3 id=3D"C_DiscreteMathematics-Example">Example</h3>
<p>Prove that (1 + 2 + 3 + =E2=80=A6 + n =3D \frac{n(n+1)}{2}).</p>
<ol start=3D"1">
<li>
<p><strong>Base Case:</strong> n =3D 1 =E2=86=92 LHS =3D 1, RHS =3D 1(1+1)/=
2 =3D 1 =E2=9C=85</p></li>
<li>
<p><strong>Induction Hypothesis:</strong> Assume true for n =3D k =E2=86=92=
 1 + =E2=80=A6 + k =3D k(k+1)/2</p></li>
<li>
<p><strong>Induction Step:</strong> For n =3D k+1 =E2=86=92<br>
[<br>
1 + 2 + =E2=80=A6 + k + (k+1) =3D \frac{k(k+1)}{2} + (k+1) =3D \frac{(k+1)(=
k+2)}{2}<br>
]<br>
=E2=9C=85 Statement proven.</p></li>
</ol>
<hr>
<h2 id=3D"C_DiscreteMathematics-=F0=9F=94=B93.ProofbyContradiction">=F0=9F=
=94=B9 <strong>3. Proof by Contradiction</strong></h2>
<h3 id=3D"C_DiscreteMathematics-Definition.1">Definition</h3>
<p><strong>Proof by contradiction</strong> assumes that the statement to be=
 proven is <strong>false</strong> and shows that this assumption <strong>le=
ads to a contradiction</strong>.</p>
<ul>
<li>
<p>If assuming =C2=ACP leads to a logical inconsistency, then P must be tru=
e.</p></li>
</ul>
<h3 id=3D"C_DiscreteMathematics-Example.1">Example</h3>
<p>Prove: (\sqrt{2}) is irrational.</p>
<ol start=3D"1">
<li>
<p>Assume (\sqrt{2}) is rational =E2=86=92 (\sqrt{2} =3D p/q), where gcd(p,=
 q) =3D 1</p></li>
<li>
<p>Square both sides =E2=86=92 2 =3D p=C2=B2/q=C2=B2 =E2=86=92 p=C2=B2 =3D =
2q=C2=B2 =E2=86=92 p=C2=B2 is even =E2=86=92 p is even =E2=86=92 p =3D 2k</=
p></li>
<li>
<p>Substitute back =E2=86=92 (2k)=C2=B2 =3D 2q=C2=B2 =E2=86=92 4k=C2=B2 =3D=
 2q=C2=B2 =E2=86=92 q=C2=B2 =3D 2k=C2=B2 =E2=86=92 q=C2=B2 even =E2=86=92 q=
 even</p></li>
<li>
<p>Both p and q even =E2=86=92 gcd(p, q) =E2=89=A0 1 =E2=9D=8C Contradictio=
n<br>
=E2=9C=85 Hence, (\sqrt{2}) is irrational.</p></li>
</ol>
<hr>
<h2 id=3D"C_DiscreteMathematics-=F0=9F=94=B94.Recursion">=F0=9F=94=B9 <stro=
ng>4. Recursion</strong></h2>
<h3 id=3D"C_DiscreteMathematics-Definition.2">Definition</h3>
<p><strong>Recursion</strong> is a method of defining <strong>functions or =
sequences</strong> in terms of <strong>smaller instances of themselves</str=
ong>.</p>
<ul>
<li>
<p>It is widely used in algorithms, programming, and mathematical proofs.</=
p></li>
</ul>
<h3 id=3D"C_DiscreteMathematics-Example.2">Example</h3>
<p><strong>Factorial function</strong>:<br>
[<br>
n! =3D \begin{cases}<br>
1 &amp; \text{if } n =3D 0 \<br>
n \cdot (n-1)! &amp; \text{if } n &gt; 0<br>
\end{cases}<br>
]</p>
<p><strong>Fibonacci sequence:</strong><br>
[<br>
F(n) =3D \begin{cases}<br>
0 &amp; n=3D0 \<br>
1 &amp; n=3D1 \<br>
F(n-1) + F(n-2) &amp; n&gt;1<br>
\end{cases}<br>
]</p>
<h3 id=3D"C_DiscreteMathematics-RelationwithInduction">Relation with Induct=
ion</h3>
<ul>
<li>
<p>Recursive definitions often lead to <strong>proofs by mathematical induc=
tion</strong>, since each step depends on previous cases.</p></li>
</ul>
<hr>
<h2 id=3D"C_DiscreteMathematics-=E2=9C=855.SummaryTable">=E2=9C=85 <strong>=
5. Summary Table</strong></h2>
<div class=3D"table-wrap">
<table data-layout=3D"default" data-local-id=3D"bdeea0fd-592d-4e07-a270-095=
d30ea87af" class=3D"confluenceTable">
<tbody>
<tr>
<th class=3D"confluenceTh">
<p>Concept</p></th>
<th class=3D"confluenceTh">
<p>Key Idea</p></th>
<th class=3D"confluenceTh">
<p>Example</p></th>
</tr>
<tr>
<td class=3D"confluenceTd">
<p><strong>Induction</strong></p></td>
<td class=3D"confluenceTd">
<p>Prove true for all n by base + step</p></td>
<td class=3D"confluenceTd">
<p>Sum of first n numbers</p></td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td class=3D"confluenceTd">
<p><strong>Contradiction</strong></p></td>
<td class=3D"confluenceTd">
<p>Assume false =E2=86=92 show impossible</p></td>
<td class=3D"confluenceTd">
<p>(\sqrt{2}) is irrational</p></td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td class=3D"confluenceTd">
<p><strong>Recursion</strong></p></td>
<td class=3D"confluenceTd">
<p>Define in terms of smaller instances</p></td>
