<ol start=3D"6">
<li>
<p>Counting; Principles of inclusion and exclusion;</p></li>
</ol>
<p>Let=E2=80=99s explain <strong>Counting</strong> and <strong>Principles o=
f Inclusion and Exclusion (PIE)</strong>, which are core topics in <strong>=
Discrete Mathematics</strong>.</p>
<hr>
<h2 id=3D"C_DiscreteMathematics-=F0=9F=A7=A91.Counting(Combinatorics)">=F0=
=9F=A7=A9 <strong>1. Counting (Combinatorics)</strong></h2>
<h3 id=3D"C_DiscreteMathematics-=F0=9F=94=B9Definition.4">=F0=9F=94=B9 Defi=
nition</h3>
<p><strong>Counting</strong> or <strong>combinatorics</strong> is the study=
 of <strong>ways to select or arrange objects</strong>.<br>
It helps in <strong>enumerating possibilities</strong>, which is essential =
for probability, algorithms, and discrete structures.</p>
<hr>
<h3 id=3D"C_DiscreteMathematics-=F0=9F=94=B9BasicCountingPrinciples">=F0=9F=
=94=B9 Basic Counting Principles</h3>
<ol start=3D"1">
<li>
<p><strong>Addition Principle</strong></p>
<ul>
<li>
<p>If there are <strong>m ways</strong> to do task A and <strong>n ways</st=
rong> to do task B, and tasks cannot occur together:<br>
[<br>
\text{Total ways} =3D m + n<br>
]</p></li>
</ul></li>
<li>
<p><strong>Multiplication Principle</strong></p>
<ul>
<li>
<p>If task A can be done in <strong>m ways</strong> and task B can be done =
in <strong>n ways</strong>, done sequentially:<br>
[<br>
\text{Total ways} =3D m \cdot n<br>
]</p></li>
</ul></li>
</ol>
<hr>
<h3 id=3D"C_DiscreteMathematics-=F0=9F=94=B9PermutationsandCombinations">=
=F0=9F=94=B9 Permutations and Combinations</h3>
<div class=3D"table-wrap">
<table data-layout=3D"default" data-local-id=3D"37012908-bcf0-4897-bb71-d54=
afbde11df" class=3D"confluenceTable">
<tbody>
<tr>
<th class=3D"confluenceTh">
<p>Concept</p></th>
<th class=3D"confluenceTh">
<p>Meaning</p></th>
<th class=3D"confluenceTh">
<p>Formula</p></th>
</tr>
<tr>
<td class=3D"confluenceTd">
<p><strong>Permutation (nPr)</strong></p></td>
<td class=3D"confluenceTd">
<p>Arrangements of n objects taken r at a time</p></td>
<td class=3D"confluenceTd">
<p>( nPr =3D \frac{n!}{(n-r)!} )</p></td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td class=3D"confluenceTd">
<p><strong>Combination (nCr)</strong></p></td>
<td class=3D"confluenceTd">
<p>Selections of r objects from n (order does not matter)</p></td>
<td class=3D"confluenceTd">
<p>( nCr =3D \frac{n!}{r!(n-r)!} )</p></td>
</tr>
</tbody>
</table>
</div>
<hr>
<h3 id=3D"C_DiscreteMathematics-=F0=9F=94=B9Example">=F0=9F=94=B9 Example</=
h3>
<ul>
<li>
<p>5 books, choose 2:</p>
<ul>
<li>
<p>Permutation: 5P2 =3D 5=C3=974 =3D 20 (arrangement matters)</p></li>
<li>
<p>Combination: 5C2 =3D 5=C3=974/2 =3D 10 (arrangement doesn=E2=80=99t matt=
er)</p></li>
</ul></li>
</ul>
<hr>
<h2 id=3D"C_DiscreteMathematics-=F0=9F=A7=A92.PrincipleofInclusionandExclus=
ion(PIE)">=F0=9F=A7=A9 <strong>2. Principle of Inclusion and Exclusion (PIE=
)</strong></h2>
<h3 id=3D"C_DiscreteMathematics-=F0=9F=94=B9Definition.5">=F0=9F=94=B9 Defi=
nition</h3>
<p><strong>PIE</strong> is used to <strong>count the number of elements in =
the union of overlapping sets</strong>.</p>
<ul>
<li>
<p>Direct addition of sizes <strong>overcounts elements in the intersection=
</strong>, so we subtract appropriately.</p></li>
</ul>
<h3 id=3D"C_DiscreteMathematics-=F0=9F=94=B9TwoSets">=F0=9F=94=B9 Two Sets<=
/h3>
<p>For sets A and B:<br>
[<br>
|A \cup B| =3D |A| + |B| - |A \cap B|<br>
]</p>
<h3 id=3D"C_DiscreteMathematics-=F0=9F=94=B9ThreeSets">=F0=9F=94=B9 Three S=
ets</h3>
<p>For sets A, B, C:<br>
[<br>
|A \cup B \cup C| =3D |A| + |B| + |C| - |A \cap B| - |A \cap C| - |B \cap C=
| + |A \cap B \cap C|<br>
]</p>
<h3 id=3D"C_DiscreteMathematics-=F0=9F=94=B9GeneralIdea">=F0=9F=94=B9 Gener=
al Idea</h3>
<ul>
<li>
<p><strong>Add sizes of individual sets</strong></p></li>
<li>
<p><strong>Subtract sizes of pairwise intersections</strong></p></li>
<li>
<p><strong>Add sizes of triple intersections</strong></p></li>
<li>
<p>Continue alternating =C2=B1 for higher intersections</p></li>
</ul>
<hr>
<h3 id=3D"C_DiscreteMathematics-=F0=9F=94=B9Example.1">=F0=9F=94=B9 Example=
</h3>
<p>In a class of 50 students:</p>
<ul>
<li>
<p>30 study Math (M), 25 study Physics (P), 10 study both (M=E2=88=A9P)</p>=
</li>
<li>
<p>How many study at least one?</p></li>
</ul>
<p>[<br>
|M \cup P| =3D |M| + |P| - |M \cap P| =3D 30 + 25 - 10 =3D 45<br>
]</p>
<hr>
<h3 id=3D"C_DiscreteMathematics-=F0=9F=94=B9Applications.2">=F0=9F=94=B9 Ap=
plications</h3>
<ul>
<li>
<p>Counting students in overlapping groups</p></li>
<li>
<p>Probability calculations</p></li>
<li>
<p>Solving combinatorial problems</p></li>
<li>
<p>Inclusion-exclusion principle is widely used in <strong>set theory, numb=
er theory, and computer science</strong>.</p></li>
</ul>
<hr>
